Department of Chemistry:  
  
About Department  
The Department of Chemistry was established in the year 1994.The department has well qualified and 
experienced and dedicated faculty members. The department is a recognized research department by 
Anna University, Chennai. Full time research scholars working in this department are supported by 
monthly Institutional Research Fellowship, enabling them apply for government fellowships. Research 
work in the department ranges across most challenging problems in Materials Science, Nano Science, 
Nanotechnology, Corrosion Science, Thin Films, Environmental Science, Phyto Chemistry and 
Photocatalysis.  
  
Head Of the Chemistry: Dr. L. Ragunath  
Dr. L. Ragunath has received his doctoral degree from Bharathiar University Coimbatore in the year 2013.
He completed his M.Phil in 1990 from Bharathiar University. He completed his M.Sc. in 1989 and B.Sc. in 
1987 from PSG College of Arts and Science affiliated to Bharathiar University. He has also completed 
M.A. Yoga for Human Excellence from Bharathiar University in 2018 and a PG Diploma in Guidance and 
Counselling (PGDGC) in 2000 from Annamalai University through distance education.     He has twenty

About Department  
  
               At the Department of English, highly qualified faculty with commendable teaching and research 
experience, and commitment to excellence strive to cultivate not just competent graduates, but luminaries
of engineering, science, and technology equipped with linguistic skills. The members of the faculty, each 
a Cambridge-certified speaking examiner, are on a mission to take the students on a transformative 
journey through the vast landscapes of language. Our curriculum is meticulously crafted to equip one with
the communicative prowess to navigate the global arena with confidence. The Department has been 
entrusted with the task of running SNR Sons Charitable Trust ± Cambridge English Language 
Assessment Centre (CELAC), a prestigious portal to globally acclaimed Cambridge certifications. This 
center empowers not just SREC students and faculty, but extends its reach to students from other 
institutions and even corporate entities, fostering a vibrant learning community. As language transcends 
mere communication, the Department plays a pivotal role in igniting a creative spark through diverse 
forums like the English Literary Society (ELS), the Reading Movement, and blogging initiatives. Wits are 
sharpened at the Q-Zenith Quiz Club where intellectual jousting becomes a thrilling pursuit. It is common 
knowledge that linguistic horizons extend beyond the English language. Bearing in that mind, the 
department fosters a spirit of cultural immersion by offering courses in German, Japanese, and Tamil. In a
bid to extend the application of its collective expertise beyond the classroom, the Department conducts 
regular outreach programs to hone the communication skills of school and polytechnic students, ensuring 
a strong foundation for introduction and development of essential soft skills coveted by employers. The 
Department of English envisions holistic development, and is dedicated to academic excellence and 
social responsibility, empowering the students to become not just effective communicators, but articulate 
ambassadors for the world stage.

Project title: Smart ESD and Environment Risk Monitor  
 
Abstract  
 
 
In high -precision industrial environments such as semiconductor manufacturing units, 
pharmaceutical cleanrooms, and PCB assembly lines, maintaining strict control over 
microclimatic conditions is essential. Electrostatic discharge (ESD), particulate contamination, 
and even minor fluctuations in temperature, humidity, or air pressure can lead to product 
defects, equipment ma lfunctions, or compliance failures. Despite their importance, these 
parameters are often monitored manually or using expensive, centralized systems, which can 
result in delayed responses to hazardous changes. This project addresses the need for a cost -
effective, real -time monitoring solution that can detect and alert operators about environmental 
and ESD -related risks before they escalate.  
The proposed system is a compact, edge -based device that continuously monitors key 
environmental parameters including e lectrostatic charge, particulate levels (PM2.5), 
temperature, humidity, and ambient pressure. A microcontroller processes sensor data to 
compute a real -time hazard score, displayed on an OLED screen with visual and audio alerts 
for critical conditions. The  system also supports data logging and optional MQTT -based 
communication for centralized dashboards. Designed to be portable and energy -efficient, this 
solution can be deployed across multiple industrial zones, providing real -time insights to 
quality assur ance and maintenance teams. The project offers a practical approach to enhancing 
industrial safety and process reliability, while aligning with Industry 4.0 standards .

An Introduction to Personal Protective Equipment (PPE)
Personal Protective Equipment, commonly referred to as PPE, encompasses any
specialized equipment, clothing, or device worn by an individual to minimize their
exposure to specific workplace hazards that could cause injury or illness 
(safetyservicesdirect.com) . According to the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration (OSHA), these hazards may be chemical, radiological, physical,
electrical, mechanical, or other environmental threats (osha.gov) . In industrial settings,
PPE is the final and crucial line of defense in the hierarchy of hazard controls,
implemented when engineering and administrative controls cannot completely
eliminate risks.

component of a comprehensive safety program, acting as a barrier between the worker
and the hazardous environment. The consequences of neglecting its use are severe and
multifaceted. Workers may face a spectrum of injuries, from minor cuts and burns to
debilitating long-term health conditions such as respiratory diseases, skin conditions,
and noise-induced hearing loss (forkliftsafety.com) . In the most tragic cases, the
absence of proper PPE, such as hard hats or fall protection, can lead to fatalities 
(gibadi.com) . Beyond the human cost, companies that fail to enforce PPE usage face
significant legal liabilities, regulatory fines, and financial losses due to decreased
productivity and increased insurance premiums. Therefore, a robust PPE program,
centered on proper selection, training, and maintenance, is an indispensable pillar of a
safe, ethical, and productive industrial operation.1 / 8

Head Protection
Head protection is vital in environments where there's a risk of head injury from falling
objects, impacts, or electrical hazards. * Hard Hats:  These are essential on most
industrial and construction sites. They are classified into two types: Type I  hats protect
from blows to the top of the head, while Type II  hats offer protection from top and
lateral impacts (studson.com) . They also come in different classes for electrical
protection. * Bump Caps:  These are designed for low-risk areas where workers may
bump their heads on stationary objects but are not at risk from falling items. They do
not offer the same level of impact protection as hard hats (ehs.ncsu.edu) .
Eye and Face Protection
This category of PPE shields the user from a variety of hazards that can cause serious
eye or facial injury. * Safety Glasses:  The most common form of eye protection, they
provide impact resistance and often have side shields to protect from particles entering
from the side (esafety.com) . * Goggles:  These provide a tighter seal around the eyes
than glasses, offering superior protection against chemical splashes, dust, and fine
particles (michelli.com) . * Face Shields:  Offering broader protection for the entire
face, face shields are considered secondary protection and must be worn in conjunction
with safety glasses or goggles to provide adequate eye protection against impact and
splashes (ehs.wsu.edu) .
Hand Protection
Hands are frequently exposed to hazards, making gloves a critical piece of PPE. The
material and design vary widely based on the specific risk. * Leather, Canvas, or
Metal Mesh Gloves:  Offer protection against cuts, punctures, and burns 
(ehs.princeton.edu) . * Chemical-Resistant Gloves:  Made from materials like nitrile,
neoprene, or butyl rubber, these gloves are selected based on the specific chemical
being handled to prevent skin contact and absorption (ehsinsight.com) . * Coated
Fabric Gloves:  These provide enhanced grip and resistance to abrasion and are
commonly used in general manufacturing and material handling (jcblhandtools.com) .3 / 8

Safety footwear protects against a multitude of hazards present in industrial

Includes boots with metatarsal guards for upper foot protection, puncture-resistant

Hearing Protection
Prolonged exposure to loud noise can cause permanent hearing damage. Hearing
protection reduces the level of noise reaching the eardrum. * Earplugs:  Inserted into
the ear canal, these can be disposable (foam) or reusable (pre-molded) (hexarmor.com) .
They are effective and portable. * Earmuffs:  These devices fit over the entire outer ear,
creating a seal to block sound. They are easy to put on and take off, making them
suitable for intermittent noise exposure (pnwaudiology.com) . In extremely loud
environments, wearing earplugs and earmuffs together provides maximum protection.

respirators with chemical cartridges (ccohs.ca) . * Supplied-Air Respirators (SARs):

atmospheres or when contaminant concentrations are immediately dangerous to life or

From Theory to Practice: Proper PPE Usage
Selecting the right PPE is only half the battle; using it correctly is what ensures its
effectiveness. Proper usage involves meticulous procedures for donning and doffing,
awareness of common mistakes, and comprehensive worker training.
Donning and Doffing Procedures
The sequence for putting on (donning) and taking off (doffing) PPE is designed to
prevent self-contamination. While the exact order can vary based on the specific PPE
ensemble, the principle is to contain contaminants. A general CDC-recommended
sequence is:
Donning (Putting On):
Step 1: Gown/Coveralls:  Put on the protective suit and secure all fasteners 
(dhs.wisconsin.gov) .
Step 2: Mask or Respirator:  Secure ties or elastic bands. Perform a user
seal check if using a respirator.
Step 3: Goggles or Face Shield:  Place over the face and eyes and adjust to
fit.
Step 4: Gloves:  Extend gloves to cover the wrist of the isolation gown or
suit.
Doffing (Taking Off):  This process removes the most contaminated items first.
Step 1: Gloves and Gown/Coveralls:  These are often removed together. The
exterior is considered contaminated.
Step 2: Hand Hygiene:  Immediately wash hands or use an alcohol-based
sanitizer.
Step 3: Goggles or Face Shield:  Remove from the back by lifting the
headband. Avoid touching the front (mirsafety.com) .

Common Mistakes to Avoid
Many PPE failures stem from simple, avoidable errors. * Improper Fit:  This is one of
the most critical mistakes. PPE that is too loose or too tight will not provide adequate
protection. For example, an ill-fitting respirator allows contaminated air to leak in,
while loose gloves can get caught in machinery (cos.net.au) . * Incorrect Selection:
Using PPE not designed for the specific hazard, such as using cloth gloves to handle
chemicals, provides a false sense of security and can be extremely dangerous 
(cprcertificationnow.com) . * Reusing Disposable PPE:  Single-use items, like some
gloves and masks, are not designed to be cleaned or reused and lose their protective
integrity after one use. * Complacency and Lack of Enforcement:  Over time,
workers may become complacent and skip steps or fail to wear their PPE. Supervisors
must consistently enforce PPE policies.
The Critical Role of Training and Fit
OSHA mandates that employers provide workers with comprehensive training on PPE.
This training must cover the limitations of the equipment and how to properly don,
doff, adjust, wear, and care for it. Crucially, a "one-size-fits-all" approach is no longer
acceptable. OSHA has clarified its rules, effective January 2025, to explicitly state that
PPE must fit each worker properly based on their individual body size and type 
(ishn.com) . Employers must provide a range of sizes and conduct fit-testing, especially
for tight-fitting respirators, to ensure every worker is protected.

Ensuring Reliability: PPE Maintenance and Lifecycles
To remain effective, PPE requires a diligent program of inspection, cleaning, proper
storage, and timely replacement. Well-maintained equipment is essential for protecting
worker safety.
Inspection Routines
Regular inspection is the first line of defense against equipment failure. * Daily Pre-
Use Checks:  Before each use, workers must perform a visual inspection of their PPE.

CHUNKING — TYPES, WHEN TO USE, LOGISTICS EXAMPLES
A) Fixed-size (chars/tokens) with overlap
What: cut every N tokens (e.g., 800) with 100–150 token overlap.
Pros: simple, fast, consistent.
Cons: can split mid-sentence/clause.
Use when: quick prototype; mixed prose.
Logistics ex: split a 30-page operations SOP into uniform chunks.
B) Sentence/paragraph boundary chunking
What: split on sentence/paragraph, then merge until size limit.
Pros: semantic integrity; fewer “half ideas”.
Cons: uneven sizes; still may be large.
Use when: manuals, FAQs, knowledge bases.

EMBEDDING:
1. What is Embedding?
In simple words:
Embedding = converting text into numbers (vectors) so that a computer/LLM can understand and compare meanings.
These numbers (vectors) live in a vector database where "similar meanings" are stored close together.
🔹 2. Why Embedding in Your Topic?
Let’s say you have 100 DHL contracts (PDFs).
Now you want to ask:
“What’s the late delivery penalty in DHL’s June 2025 contract?”
The system can’t directly read PDF text as words.
So first, we chunk it (e.g., 200 words with overlap).
Then we embed each chunk → convert into vectors.
When you query, “late delivery penalty”, the query is also embedded into a vector.
The system searches which chunk vector is closest in meaning → retrieves that contract clause.
3. Types of Embeddings
There are different kinds of embeddings depending on what meaning you want to capture:
(A) Text Embeddings (most common for RAG)
Convert sentences/paragraphs into vectors.
Used for searching meaning in documents.
Example in logistics:
“late delivery penalty” → becomes a vector.
The contract sentence “If goods are delivered late, 5% of invoice value will be charged” → becomes another vector.
Since both are close in meaning, the system retrieves it.

PARCEL LIFE CYCLE
Order and Booking: The Customer books the product through online and this order was packed, labelled and hand overed to the courier partner 
First Mile Pickup: The Courier partner collects the parcel from the senders location and shift it to the nearest hub.
Local Sorting: The orders are shorted based on the delivery PIN code and the address. Here the product is scanned and the customer got the update. Then it was sent to the Regional Distribution Centre.
Transportation: The product is transported to the central hub which is the long journey via flight or train or truck.
Nearest Hub Arrival: Once the product got arrived the product is again scanned for status updating. It gets sorted by the delivery zones.
Distribution: once sorted the parcel is assigned for the individual delivery agent and the product is delivered.
Reverse Logistics: If the product is returned the process will happened in the reverse order.
